│ stop({"edit_points": [[553, 581,                                         │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanUnroll.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.       │
│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe loop-vectorizer crashes when destroying a  │
│ VPReplicateRecipe (for the scalar compare %c) during                     │
│ VPlanTransforms::replicateByVF. The assertion \"trying to delete a       │
│ VPValue with remaining users\" indicates the recipe still has users when │
│ erased. This happens inside replicateByVF(), which transforms            │
│ VPReplicateRecipe nodes into per-lane scalar clones and then removes the │
│ original recipe. Some users of the original replicated value aren't      │
│ updated to use the new per-lane values (or a constructed vector from     │
│ them), leaving dangling uses on the original VPValue.\n\n2. Analyzing    │
│ opt's Log:\n- VPlan shows: REPLICATE ir<%c> = fcmp ogt ir<%l>, ...;      │
│ WIDEN-SELECT ir<%base> = select ir<%c>, ...\n- %c is scalarized (a       │
│ VPReplicateRecipe). The widen select uses %c directly as its condition   │
│ operand.\n- replicateByVF logs show it's the pass that runs before the   │
│ crash; the backtrace pinpoints eraseFromParent() called from             │
│ replicateByVF.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nWithin replicateByVF(), for a │
│ VPReplicateRecipe RepR, we:\n- Create per-lane clones (LaneDefs).\n-     │
│ Replace uses that only demand the first lane with LaneDefs[0].\n-        │
│ Special-case BuildVector/BuildStructVector users to expand their         │
│ operands to all lanes.\n- Then erase RepR at the end of the              │
│ pass.\n\nHowever, users that expect a vector operand (e.g.,              │
│ WIDEN-SELECT, or other widen recipes) and currently refer directly to    │
│ RepR are not updated. In our reproducer, WIDEN-SELECT still uses the     │
│ original %c after we've created per-lane clones, so when we erase RepR,  │
│ it still has users, triggering the assertion in                          │
│ VPValue::~VPValue.\n\nThe code assumes all remaining users will either   │
│ be first-lane-only (handled), build vectors (handled), or will           │
│ themselves be VPReplicateRecipes processed later; but the widen          │
│ instructions are neither: they are VPInstruction users that expect a     │
