│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                              │
│                                                                          │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                          │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                              │
│ The loop-vectorizer crashes when destroying a VPReplicateRecipe (for the │
│ scalar compare %c) during VPlanTransforms::replicateByVF. The assertion  │
│ "trying to delete a VPValue with remaining users" indicates the recipe   │
│ still has users when erased. This happens inside replicateByVF(), which  │
│ transforms VPReplicateRecipe nodes into per-lane scalar clones and then  │
│ removes the original recipe. Some users of the original replicated value │
│ aren't updated to use the new per-lane values (or a constructed vector   │
│ from them), leaving dangling uses on the original VPValue.               │
│                                                                          │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                  │
│ - VPlan shows: REPLICATE ir<%c> = fcmp ogt ir<%l>, ...; WIDEN-SELECT     │
│ ir<%base> = select ir<%c>, ...                                           │
│ - %c is scalarized (a VPReplicateRecipe). The widen select uses %c       │
│ directly as its condition operand.                                       │
│ - replicateByVF logs show it's the pass that runs before the crash; the  │
│ backtrace pinpoints eraseFromParent() called from replicateByVF.         │
│                                                                          │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                  │
│ Within replicateByVF(), for a VPReplicateRecipe RepR, we:                │
│ - Create per-lane clones (LaneDefs).                                     │
│ - Replace uses that only demand the first lane with LaneDefs[0].         │
│ - Special-case BuildVector/BuildStructVector users to expand their       │
│ operands to all lanes.                                                   │
│ - Then erase RepR at the end of the pass.                                │
│                                                                          │
│ However, users that expect a vector operand (e.g., WIDEN-SELECT, or      │
│ other widen recipes) and currently refer directly to RepR are not        │
│ updated. In our reproducer, WIDEN-SELECT still uses the original %c      │
│ after we've created per-lane clones, so when we erase RepR, it still has │
│ users, triggering the assertion in VPValue::~VPValue.                    │
│                                                                          │
│ The code assumes all remaining users will either be first-lane-only      │
│ (handled), build vectors (handled), or will themselves be                │
│ VPReplicateRecipes processed later; but the widen instructions are       │
│ neither: they are VPInstruction users that expect a vector, and we must  │
│ provide them a vector value (a buildvector of the lane defs) and         │
│ redirect their uses before deleting RepR.                                │
│                                                                          │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                               │
│ File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanUnroll.cpp                      │
│ Location: In VPlanTransforms::replicateByVF, after creating LaneDefs for │
│ a RepR and after updating Build(Vector|StructVector) users, but before   │
│ pushing RepR to ToRemove (around lines 553–581).                         │
│                                                                          │
│ Change: After computing LaneDefs and adjusting                           │
│ Build(Vector|StructVector) users, if RepR still has users, insert a      │
│ BuildVector VPInstruction from the lane defs and replace remaining uses  │
│ of RepR with that BuildVector, excluding VPReplicateRecipe users (which  │
│ will be transformed later using Def2LaneDefs). This ensures widen        │
│ recipes (like select/icmp/fcmp/etc.) receive a proper vector operand and │
│ that RepR ends up with no users by the time we erase it.                 │
│                                                                          │
│ Pseudo-code to add before `ToRemove.push_back(RepR);`:                   │
│                                                                          │
│ - if (RepR->getNumUsers()) {                                             │
│     VPInstruction *BV = Builder.createNaryOp(VPInstruction::BuildVector, │
│ LaneDefs);                                                               │
│     RepR->replaceUsesWithIf(BV, [](VPUser &U, unsigned) { return         │
│ !isa<VPReplicateRecipe>(&U); });                                         │
│   }                                                                      │
│                                                                          │
│ This keeps VPReplicateRecipe users intact (they will be processed and    │
│ remapped to per-lane operands using Def2LaneDefs), and redirects all     │
│ other remaining users (notably widen instructions like Select) to a      │
│ vector built from the lanes.                                             │
│                                                                          │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                           │
│ The crash is caused by replicateByVF erasing a VPReplicateRecipe that    │
│ still has live users (e.g., WIDEN-SELECT conditions). By constructing a  │
│ BuildVector from the per-lane clones and redirecting non-Replicate users │
│ to it before erasing the original recipe, we guarantee Users.empty()     │
│ holds, preventing the assertion. This also preserves correct semantics   │
│ for widen recipes expecting vector operands, while allowing replicate    │
│ users to be transformed later in the same pass.                          │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                          │
