  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe loop-vectorizer crashes
when destroying a VPReplicateRecipe (for the scalar compare %c) during
VPlanTransforms::replicateByVF. The assertion \"trying to delete a VPValue
with remaining users\" indicates the recipe still has users when erased.
This happens inside replicateByVF(), which transforms VPReplicateRecipe
nodes into per-lane scalar clones and then removes the original recipe. Some
users of the original replicated value aren't updated to use the new
per-lane values (or a constructed vector from them), leaving dangling uses
on the original VPValue.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n- VPlan shows:
REPLICATE ir<%c> = fcmp ogt ir<%l>, ...; WIDEN-SELECT ir<%base> = select
ir<%c>, ...\n- %c is scalarized (a VPReplicateRecipe). The widen select uses
%c directly as its condition operand.\n- replicateByVF logs show it's the
pass that runs before the crash; the backtrace pinpoints eraseFromParent()
called from replicateByVF.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nWithin
replicateByVF(), for a VPReplicateRecipe RepR, we:\n- Create per-lane clones
(LaneDefs).\n- Replace uses that only demand the first lane with
LaneDefs[0].\n- Special-case BuildVector/BuildStructVector users to expand
their operands to all lanes.\n- Then erase RepR at the end of the
pass.\n\nHowever, users that expect a vector operand (e.g., WIDEN-SELECT, or
other widen recipes) and currently refer directly to RepR are not updated.
In our reproducer, WIDEN-SELECT still uses the original %c after we've
created per-lane clones, so when we erase RepR, it still has users,
triggering the assertion in VPValue::~VPValue.\n\nThe code assumes all
remaining users will either be first-lane-only (handled), build vectors
(handled), or will themselves be VPReplicateRecipes processed later; but the
widen instructions are neither: they are VPInstruction users that expect a
vector, and we must provide them a vector value (a buildvector of the lane
defs) and redirect their uses before deleting RepR.\n\n4. Proposed Edit
Point(s):\nFile: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanUnroll.cpp\nLocation: In
VPlanTransforms::replicateByVF, after creating LaneDefs for a RepR and after
updating Build(Vector|StructVector) users, but before pushing RepR to
ToRemove (around lines 553\u2013581).\n\nChange: After computing LaneDefs
and adjusting Build(Vector|StructVector) users, if RepR still has users,
insert a BuildVector VPInstruction from the lane defs and replace remaining
uses of RepR with that BuildVector, excluding VPReplicateRecipe users (which
will be transformed later using Def2LaneDefs). This ensures widen recipes
(like select/icmp/fcmp/etc.) receive a proper vector operand and that RepR
ends up with no users by the time we erase it.\n\nPseudo-code to add before
`ToRemove.push_back(RepR);`:\n\n- if (RepR->getNumUsers()) {\n
VPInstruction *BV = Builder.createNaryOp(VPInstruction::BuildVector,
LaneDefs);\n    RepR->replaceUsesWithIf(BV, [](VPUser &U, unsigned) { return
!isa<VPReplicateRecipe>(&U); });\n  }\n\nThis keeps VPReplicateRecipe users
intact (they will be processed and remapped to per-lane operands using
Def2LaneDefs), and redirects all other remaining users (notably widen
instructions like Select) to a vector built from the lanes.\n\n5.
Conclusion:\nThe crash is caused by replicateByVF erasing a
VPReplicateRecipe that still has live users (e.g., WIDEN-SELECT conditions).
By constructing a BuildVector from the per-lane clones and redirecting
non-Replicate users to it before erasing the original recipe, we guarantee
Users.empty() holds, preventing the assertion. This also preserves correct
semantics for widen recipes expecting vector operands, while allowing
replicate users to be transformed later in the same pass.",
